{"/service/ndnp/lu/batch_lu_jacobi_ver01/data/sn88064250/00212475671/1908031401/0341.xml":{"full_text":"The St, IUEtJ (LG.) Esis Isulet51 L@S\u00a30\nTHE ST LANDRY CLARION.\n\"Here Shall The Press The People's Rights Maintain, Unawed by influence and Unbribed by Cain.\"\nVOL. XVIII.---NO. 24. OPELOUSAS, LA., SATURDAY, MARCH 14,1908. $1PER YEAR\n.t r- t I I I u\nA GREAT FEAT\nOF ENGINEERING\nIs the Colorado Southern Use Through the\nAtcbefalaya Swamps.\nBRIDGE IS A HARD PROBLEM\nUaprecedented Stage of Water In the liver Has\nMade foal Completion of the Bridge la.\npossible Noew-Line Through Swamp.\nAn excursion given by the officials\nof the Frisco to the police jury and\ncitizens of the parish left Crowley\nSaturday morning and visited the\nscene of the bridge construction over\nthe Atchafalaya river, returning\ntwelve hours later. About 200 pas\nsengers were aboard the train, which\nconsisted of an engine, a baggage car\nused as an improvised diner and five\ncoaches. The Frisco officials furnished\nlunch and cigars for their guests and\nthe Rice City Band was aboard the\ntrain, says the Crowley Signal.\nThe object of the excursion was to\ngive the police jury and the citizens\nof the territory in the parish tra\nversed by the road an opportunity to[\nexamine the line and particularly to\nshow the police jury the difficulties\nthat had been encountered by the rail\nroad company in building through the\nAtchafalaya swamp and throwing a\nbridge across the Atchafalaya river.\nThis latter undertaking has delayed\nthe completion of the road beyond\nthe time specified in the contract of\nthe railroad company with this and\nother parishes and it became neces\nsary to grant the road an extension\nof time. It was for the purpose of\nshowing that the request for this ex\ntension was reasonable that the trip\nover the line was taken.\nThe Atchafalaya is twenty miles\neast of Opelousas and the railroad\ntrack is completed to the river bank.\nIt is also completed from Baton Rouge\nto the east bank of the river. West\nof the river twelve miles of the road\nruns through swamps filled with water,\nand east of the river it runs eight\nmiles through the same kind of terri\ntory. These twenty miles of swamp\nhad been built through with extreme\ndifficulty. Every foot of the twenty\nmiles is trestle work built on piling\nand filled in with earth hauled from a\npoint near Opelousas. For months\nthere has been a high stage of water\nin the swamp and it has been very\ndifficult to keep men at work on ac\ncount of the arduous and unhealthy\ncharacter of the task. Most laborers\nrefused to stay more than a few days\non account of their feet becoming sore\nfrom working in the water.\nBuilding a railroad line capable of\nsustaining the heaviest traffic through\nthis twenty miles of swamp was i'\nitself no mean feat of engineering,\nbut bridging the Atchafalaya river\nhas proved to be an extremely diffi\ncult problem. From bank to bank\nthe river is about 1200 feet wide at\nthis point. Under ordinary circum\nstances it has about fifty feet of\nwater. On Saturday it had about\nninety feet. That is, the water in\nthe Atchafalaya on March 7 was forty\nfeet above its average stage. This\nwas produced by the recent rises in\nthe rivers of the upper Mississippi\nand Ohio valleys and by the rains of\nthe past few months, which have kept\nthe river up since last fall.\nAnother cause which has contribu\nted in no small degree to the great\nrise in the Atchafalaya is the con\nstruction by the government of lev\nees which have prevented the river\nfrom spreading over twenty miles of\nswamps, except by backing up fpom\nthe point below which the levee is\nconstructed. The levee is now built\nto the railroad on the west bank of\nthe river, and the rapidity with\nwhich the water is backing in from\nbelow is shown by the swift current\nalong the road for several miles west\nof the river.\nThere will be about 1,300 feet of\niron bridge when the work is com\npleted. Already about 1,000 feet of\nthe bridge is in place and the piers\nare built for the balance. All the\nmaterial is on the ground and only\nthe high water prevents the immedi\nate completion of the structure.\nThe stone piers from which the\nbridge will be suspended rest on\nwillow mattresses covered by vast\nquantities of stone. The stone on\nwhich these pillows -.st cost the\nrailroad company $100,000.\nWhile the present stage of water is\nhigher than any previously recorded,\nit is expected to rise higher in about\ntwo weeks, when the crest of the rise\nin the Ohio reaches here. After the\nusual spring rise in the Mississippi it\nis hoped that the water will recede\nsnufliciently to allow of the rapid com\npletign of the bridge.\nIt is plain even to the inexperienced\neye that the Frisco engineers have\nhad to contend with conditions which\nmade completion of the line through\nthe Atchafaiaya inside the specified l\ntime practically impossible. The\ncompletion of the work even under\nthe most favorable conditions would\nbe looked upon as a remarkable feat\nof engineering. Other engineering\nfeats have been more spectacular, but\nfew have been more difficult.\nThe track of the Frisco from Crow\nley to Opelousas is in fine condition.\nThis is shown by the smoothness of\nmovement of trains. This is parti\ncularly the case between Eunice and\nOpelousas, although the Crowley line\nis in fine shape. From Opelousas to\nthe river the track is necessarly\nrough, on account of the constant\npounding of the heavy springless work\ntrains.\nThe excursionists returned thor\noughly pleased with their trip and\nwith the hospitable treatment accord\ned them by those in charge of the\nexcursion. On the return trip a\nshortstop was made at Opelousas.\nCHANIE TO HEAR LECTUIRE\nConfederate Orator to Speak at Courthouse on\nlarch Seventeenth.\nDr. Sam Steel the famous Texas\norator, will deliver his lecture, \"Home\nLife in Dixie in War Timds,\" at the\ncourthouse, in Opelousas, on the night\nof Tuesday, March 17.\nThe money derived from the lecture\nwill go to the Methodist Parsonage\nFund. Admission 50 cents.\nThe lecture is \"a humorous account\nof the folks who staid at home in the\nSouth during the war for Southern\nIndependence,\" and the press com\nments rank Dr. Steel with the fore\nmost orators of the Southland.\nThe advance sheets of the lecture\nsay of Dr. Steel.\n\"Dr. Steel is a native of Mississippi.\nHis early life was spent on a planta\ntion amid the turbulent scenes of the\nwar for the independence of the Con\nfeedrate States, and in that severe\nschool he learned those lessons of\nself-reliance, fearlessness, and push,\nthat have been characteristic of his\ncareer. He entered the ministry\nwhen very young, rose rapidly to the\nfront, and has served the largest\nchurches of his denomination.\n\"As preacher, editor, and author,\nDr. Steel has achieved an enviable\nreputation.\n\"As a lecturer he is both enter\nbaining and instructive. Believing\nbha', oratory is a fine art, he has\nstudied it with his usual intensity of\ninterest, and his addresses are master\npieces of eloquence. His lectures,\n\"Home Life in Dixie During the War,\"\nand \"Before and After Appomattox,\"\nare made up of personal recollections\nthat vividly portray the social condi\ntion of the South during the memor\nable struggle. The subject is unique,\nthe information it conveys highly\nvaluable from an historical standpoint,\nthe incidents irresistibly ludicrous,\nand the spirit intensely patriotic.\nThese lectures have been delivered\nfrom Boston to San Francisco, and in\nevery Southern state, and whether\nheard in the North or the Sonth,\nnever fail to delight his audience.\nCol. Geo. W. Bain, himself one of the\nmost popular lecturers on the plat\nform, says \"Home Life in Dixie Dur\ning the War\" is inimitable.\n\"Dr. Steel's other lectures are\nbrimful of life, color, and humor. He\nis an orator, a poet, a story-teller, a\nkeen observer of men, and a student\nwho masters his themes and knows\nwhat the people enjoy. His aim is\nhigh, and he seldom disappoints those\nwho hear him.\"\nTHE GULF COAST LEAGUE.\nTurning Down of Alexandria by Cotten States\nLeague Revives Interest In Old League.\nThe turning down of the application\nAlexandria of and Lake Charles for\nberths in the Cotton States League\nhas revived interest in the Gulf Coast\nLeague, and it is probable that it will\nbe re-organized for this season.\nThe Clubs composing it will likely\nbe Lake Charles, Alexandria, Orange\nand Lafayette, with Crowley, Beau\nmont and Port Arthur to select from\nfor the other two teams.\nFoster-Bodemuller.\nJ. F. Foster and Miss Rosa Bode\nmuller were married at 8 o'clock on\nWednesday morning at the Catholic\nchurch here by Rev. Father Enger\nbrink, in the presence of the family\nand immediate friends. Mr. and Mrs.\nFoster will make Beaumont, Texas,\ntheir future home.\nMr. Foster is an Engineer on the\nColorado Southern, New Orleans\nPacific Railway, and Miss Rosa Bode\nmuller is the accomplished daughter\nof our fellow-townsman, Mr. Emile\nBodemuller.\nThe Clarion wishes this young\ncouple a full measure of happiness on\nthe matrimonial sea.\nBuilding A Home.\nMr. Pe`\\i Richard islhaving a home\nerected on Vine street, in the Pavy\nAddition.\nALL BELIEVE BETTER\nTIMES NEAR AT HAND\nRairead Ben so Testify to Federal Coemis\nslo In Washlngton.\nWILL NOT REDUCE WASES\nWilling to Meet Nine-lour Law Because of\nTheir Confldtnce that the Future Has in\nStore hneral Prosperity.\nWashington dispatches say that a\nremarkable fact indicating the sound\ncondition of the country at bottom\ndeveloped during the hearings just\nconcluded before the United States\nInterstate Commerce Commission\nwherein the railroad officials, while\npleading for a postponement of the\noperation of the nine-hour law, yet\nagreed not to fight it in the courts.\nNot a single official of a single rail\nway line who appeared before the\ncommission, however, expressed the\nbelief that the present industrial de\npression would be lasting. In the\ntestimony of nearly every witness be\nfore the commission, there was a note\nof confidence because nearly everyone\nof them practically believed that the\nstringency in the money market from\nwhich the country has suffered is not\ndue to fundamental causes. They\npractically uniformly express confi\ndence that the return of prosperity\nwill be almost as sudden as was the\ncoming of adversity and in their ar\nguments as to the enforcement of the\nnine-hour law, they pointed out to\nthe commission that such a return of\nprosperity might seriously embarrass\nthem in complying with the law be\ncause it would render it difficult to\nsecure the service of competent op\nerators in sufficient numbers to meet\nthe needs of prosperous conditions.\nWith four or five exceptions, no\nimportant roads in the country have\nexpressed the intention to reduce the\nwages of their employees. As Chair\nman Knapp of the Interstate Com\nmerce Commission expressed it: \"So\nfar as I am informed, there is no cQn\ncerted action on the part of American\nrailway companies to reduce wages.\nInstances of an intention to change\nthe scale of wages have been given,\nbut they can be said to be in no sense\ngeneral.\"\nON CATHOLIC MARRIAGES.\nRev. F. X. Brady Explains Law to io In Effect\nat faster.\nIn a clear, succinct manner, Rev.\nF. X. Brady, Pastor of St. Ignatius'\nCatholic Church, explained the laws\nof the Catholic Church on marriage\nwhich will go into effect on Easter\nSunday.\nFather Brady made an analysis of\nthe laws, and declared that while\nthey will be binding on all Catholics,\nthey will not effect those who are\nnot and never have been Catholics.\nFather Brady said:\n\"The chief point to be borne in\nmind is that after Easter any mar\nriage between Catholics is absolutely\nnull and void-that is, no real marri\nage at all-unless it is celebrated in\nthe presence of a duly qualified priest\nand two witnesses. The same is true\nof any marriage in which either of\nthe parties is or has been a Catholic.\n\"Heretofore when a Catholic, in\ndefiance of the laws of the Church,\nhas been married in a Protestant\nChruch or' a registry office, the\nChurch held the marriage to be sin\nful and sacrilegious and the parties\nguilty of a grievous sin, but the mar\nriage was held to be valid and bind\ning. After Easter such marriages\nwill be for Catholics not only sinful,\nbut invalid, and the persons will be\nno more husband and wife then they\nwere before.\n\"Catholics, therefore, who for any\nreason might be tempted into such a\ncourse must be duly forewarned of their\ndanger. This law binds all Catholics,\neven apostate or excommunicated\nCatholics. But the marriages of\nProtestants and non-CatholicS' in\ntheir churches are recognized by the\nCatholic Church as real and true\nmarriages, The Holy See, therefore,\ncannot be said to have taken a harsh\nor bigoted view of marriages with\nout the pale.\nWHO IS QUALIFIED PRIEST?\n\"It will be natuarlly asked, Who\nis the qualified priest before whom\nthe marriage -must be celebrated?\nThe answer is, the priest of the place\nwhere the marriage takes place.\nThat is to say, the parish priest, or\nif not a parish, the priest having the\ncure of the aouls or whom the bishop\nmay delegate.\n\"But suppose the parties did not\nbelong to that parish or district?\nEven so the marriage will be valid.\nThen can the priest of that parish or\ndistrict celebrate the marriage of all\nCatholics who come to him? Validly,\nyes, but he is not bound to celebrate\nthe marriage unless one or two alter\nnative conditions has been fulfilled\neither one or the other of the parties\nmust have resided in the parish a\nmonth or must have obtained per\nmission from the bishop under whom\nhe or she resides. But in case of\ngrave necessity this will not be nec\nessary.\n\"Let us suppose that two persons,\nA and B, wish to get married. If\nany priest having the care of souls\nconsents to marry them in his parish\nthey are really man and wife. They\nmust be married in the presence of\ntwo witnesses. But as a condition\nof decency and good order they are\nbound to conform to the following\nsimple regulations:' The marriage\nought to take place in the parish of\nthe bride, unless there be just cause\nfor it being celebrated elsewhere.\nIf, however, they desire to be married\nelsewhere, say in the parish of X,\nthey must ask the Bishop of X, or a\npriest authorized by him to marry\nthem, and either one or the other\nmust have resided in that parish for\na month.\n\"If they do not wish to reside\nthere, they must obtain permission\nfrom their own parish priest. They\nwill, of course, have to comply with\nthe usual conditions of receiving the\nsacrament.\nMAY MARRY THEMSELVES.\n\"If A and B should happen to be\npersons of no fixed abode, the priest\nwho marries them will have to obtain\npermission of the bishop. Let us\nsuppose that A and B are living in\nthe wilds of Australia, or where\nthere is a violent persecution of the\nChurch and they find that after a\nmonth the bishop is not accessible,\nthen they have only to call two wit\nnesses and take each other as man\nand wife in their presence and there\nmarriage will be both valid and lawful.\nOr let us suppose a much sadder case\nthat A and B have lived outside of wed\nlock and one or other of them is in\nimminent danger of death then for\nthe relief of conscience and the\nlegitimization of their offspring any\npriest may marry them if the parish\npriest is not available.\n\"It will be seen that the general\neffect of this law is one of masterly\nsimplification, insofar as it focuses\nthe conditions of validity and frees it\nas far as possible from the compli\ncations arising at a distance from the\njurisdiction of others over the con\ntracting parties.\n\"In the same spirit the Church in\nthe future will recognize no engage\nments as an impediment to marriage\nor as having canonical effect unless\nthey are made in writing and signed\nboth by the parties and the parish\npriest ,or the bishop, or at least in\nthe presence of two witnesses.\"\nRILE ON BAYOU BOEUF.\nNew Territory to be Opened for Cultivation of\nCereal In St. Landry.\nAt the meeting of the Police Jury\nMonday of this week, Mr. J. E. Bacon,\nof Boreta, on Bayou Boeuf, was\ngranted the right-of-way to cross the\npublic road with water mains, which\nhe will erect in connection with a\npumping plant, for the purpose of\nwatering about two hundred acres of\nland to be planted by Mr. Bacon in\nrice this season.\nMr. Bacon will commence the build\ning of levees at once, which will hold\nthe water on his land; and we under\nstand that he has secured the ser\nvices of Mr. F. S. Robert, one of our\nlocal surveyors and civil engineers.\nMr. Robert is a graduate of the Louis\niana State University, and is said to\nbe adept and thorough in this line of\nwork, and as rice cultivation will\ndoubtless be quite extensively engag\ned in in this parish in the near future,\nhis skill in levee work will make him\nmuch in demand.\nThe experiment of Mr. Bacon on\nBayou Boeuf will be closely watched\nby planters in this section, because\nif successful it will indicate one way\nof overcoming the ravages of the boll\nweevil.\nPenitentiary's New Chaplain.\nRev. H. S. Jones, of Ida, La., has\nassumed charge of his duties as Chap\nlain of the Louisiana State Penitenti\nary at Baton Rouge, to which position\nhe was elected by the Board of Con\ntrol.\nRev. Johns was the husband of\nHope Foster, of Opelousas, whose\nlementable death occurred a few\nweeks ago. Mrs. Johns was a dangh\nter of the late Dr. D. W. Eoster, and\na sister of Dr. Paul Foster, member\nof the School Board of St. Landry,\nand of Mrs. J. G. Lawler, of our city.\nRev. Johns is a minister in the\nMethodist Church, and has been con\nnected with the Louisiana Conference\nfor the past twenty years. He is\nalso well-known in Masonic circles,\nhaving been grand master of the Ida\nlodge, which he resigned upon accept\ning the chaplainship of the peniten\ntiary.\nlDR. McORIMACK'S\nSANITARY LECTURE\nlEmnlmalt Sestist Will Positively be In Ope\nlases on Night l NMrckh 21.\nEXPEC LAiE ATTENANGE\nDr. oCercmack has the lepatatien aet sing\nthe eMost lterestmig Speaker a the Med\nI1r3 Professiaon la the lted States.\nThe visit of Dr. J. N- McCormack,\nwho will speak under the auspices of\nthe Louisiana State Medical Society\nin Opelousas on March 21, at this\ntime is indeed opportune, when it is\nconsidered that our city is just en\ntering upon a sanitary awakening.\nThe distinguished speaker is mak\ning a tour of the United States,\nspeaking under the direction of the\ndifferent State and local medical or\nganizations, and it is said that he is\none of the most interesting speakers\nin the medical profession in the\nUnited States. His address is not in\nany sense a dry, scientific, technical\nlecture, but is, on the contrary, a\nplain, easily understood talk on mat\nters connected with sanitation and\npublic hygiene, which is of interest\nand profit to every man or woman\nwho hears it,\nThere should be an outpouring of\nmen, women and children on that\nnight. Hygiene and sanitation is a\nscience like anything else, and one\nmust know how to do it to do it ef\nfectively. The matter of the lives\nand health of ourselves and those\ndear to us is a matter of such im\nportance that no opportunity that\nwill enlighten us on the subject should\nbe allowed to escape.\nHELD UP AND BOBBED.\nOne Arrest Has Been Made and Other to\nFellow,\nWhile on their way home in a\nwagon last Saturday night, about\nthree miles south of Opelousas in the\npeaceful Bellevue neighborhood, Lei\nta Richard, Bourgeois and an\nold negro man were held up by two\nnegro highwaymen who proceeded to\nrob and cut and otherwise carry out\nthe purpose of their hold-up. Bour\ngeois and the old negro skidood; but\nRichard remained to defend the fort,\nas well as himself, and received for\nhis pains several severe cuts, or\nstabs, from one or both of his assail\nants.\nOne arrest has already been made\nin connection with this crime-that\nof Aristide Fruge. Fruge claims\nthat his brother Joe did the stabbing.\nAnd so the plot begins to thicken.\nIn the mean time Aristide remains in\ndurance vile,, and a diligent search\nwill be made for Joe.\nDoubtless bad booze is at the bot\ntom of it all, and the Prohibs will\nnow sit up and take notice of this\nlatest little Robin Hood business\nright at the very doors of St. Lan\ndry's capital. Or perhaps we can go\nbeyond this supposed direct cause of\nthe crime and study the question an\nthropologically, beginning with the\nblack babboon of the bamboo bush,\nand arrive at a truer conclusion.\nO'Bryan Elmer and Henry Savant\nwere the deputies who effected the\narrest.\nDENVFR MAKIN Blli PRE\nPARATION FOR CONVENTION\nEfforts to be Made to Persuade Delegates\nto Visit Agricultural Regions.\nThe Democratic National conven\ntion which will be held in Denver,\nJuly 7th, promises to be one of the\nmost interesting gatherings of the\npolitical party it represents that has\never been known to the history of the\nUnited States. Residents of Denver\nexpect a larger crowd to attend than\nhas ever come to any similar gather\ning in the country. Large sums of\nmoney will be spent in the entertain\nment of those who attend and the\ncity will be lavishly decorated for the\nevent. Both Democrats and Re\npublicans will join in the demonstra\ntions of hospitality.\nThe people of Colorado feel that\nto bring such a large and representa.\ntive body to the state will be of im\nmense benefit in increasing its popu\nlation and insuring its future devel\nopment. For that reason the citi\nzens of Denver have organized to\ngive the visitors the greatest display\nof Western hospitality that has ever\nbeen accorded visitors to that city.\nEfforts will be made by towns ad\njacent to Denver to persuade the\ndelegates to go in large numbers to\nthe agricultural regions of the state,\nthrough the mining camps and cross\nthe wide stock ranges in order that\nthey may see from what source Colo\nrado millions are derived. In some\nsections of Colorado land planted\nwith fruit trees sells for $1,600 an\nacre. In the beat sugar districts\nclose to Denver it is not uncommon\nto find farms of several hundred\nacres which are valued at $500 per\nacre. These peculiar land values\nare expected to .be of\u00b7 interest to\npeople from distant states as well\nas the immense mines and smelters\nfor which Colorado is widely known.\nAn effort will he made to persuade\nvisitors that Colorado is a desirable\nstate in which to locate and all who\ncome will be so hospitably treated\nthat they will go away ready to as\nsert that Colorado people are hospit\nable to strangers and loyal to their\nstate.\nBOARD OF ALDERMEN HET\nIN RE5ULAR SESSION.\nLarge Ameount of Baslaness Trusacoted Or.\nders Rallroads Traverslngt City to de\nA Few Thlags.\nThe Board of Aldermen met in re\ngular session Tuesday night and trans\nsacted quite a large amount of busi\nness.\nThe report of Marshal Hayes was\nread and accepted and referred to the\nFinance Committee. Report of A. C.\nJones and of J. J. Perrodin also read\nand accepted and referred to Finance\nCommittee.\nMoved by Roos, seconded by Evans,\nthat a committee of three, composed\nof Littell, Prof. Prescott and\nbe appointed to provide fire escapes\nfor the High School building. Carried.\nA communication was received from\nJudge E. S. Kerr, asking that he be\nauthorized to purchase necessary\ndockets and stationery for the City\nCourt. A motion to this effect by\nAlderman Lewis, seconded by Lawler,\nwas carried.\nA petition from residents. of the\nNortheastern portion of the City was\nreceived and read, and upon motion\nof Alderman Lewis, seconded by Roos,'\nthat petition be received and referred\nto the City Engtirr withlnstructjons\nto report to the Mayor, it was duly\ncarried.\nPetition of Cheney Street property\nowners for the right to lay a switch\nfrom the Colorado Southern, New Or\nleans Pacific Railroad track on that\nstreet was read, and on motion of\nLewis, seconded by Lawler, petition\nwas granted, work to be done under\nthe supervision of the Mayor, City At\ntorney and City Electrician.\nA communication from Messrs. Gar\nland Harry relative to' title of\nBellevue Street by Daigle estate read\nand on motion of Lawler, seconded\nby Evans, same was referred to City\nAttorney.\nA motion by Lewis, seconded by\nLawler, that the Street Commissioner\nbe instructed to construct necessary\ncrossing over Southern Pacific track\nat Guidry Street, was carried.\nMoved by Lewis, seconded by Law\nler, that the railroad companies trav\nersing the streets of Opelousas be re\nquired to provide proper drainage for\ntheir rights of way under supervision\nof the Board of Health.\nConvent Street, over which the 0.\nGee runs, was ordered put in con\ndition for a public thoroughfare by\nthe above road.\nMoved by Evans, seconded by Roos,\nthat the City Attorney be instructed\nto notify the Colorado Southern, New\nOrleans Pacific Railroad Company\nto construct a sidewalk on south side\nof Cheney Street in conformity with\nordinance adopted June 25, 1907,\nwithin ten days.\nThere being no further business,\nthe Board adjourned.\nSTATE HEALI CONFERENCE.\nWlnl meet This Year in the City of Aleandria,\nMarch 31 to April 2.\nPresident C. H. Irion, of the State\nBoard of Health, has issued a call for\nthe meeting of the Third State Health\nConference at Alexandria on March\n31st and April 1st and 2d.\nHe announces that thib meeting\nwill be a most important one. Beside\na number of intbresting and highly\ninstructive papers to be presented by\neminent physicians and sanitarians,\nmucl needed legislation relative to\npublic health and 'salitation wilt be\ndiscussed and drafted for presehta\ntion to the Legislature of 1908.\nThe attendance of health officers,\nparish and municipal, is particularly\ndesired, and our parish and city health\nmen should, and will doubtless, at\ntend. It is custmary-for the parish\nor municipal authorities to defray the\nexpenses of these delegates.\nThis meeting, it will be remember\ned, was held in Opelousas last year.\nRailroads of the State have granted\na one-fare rate.\nWILL STATE FROlllI\nTION BE ATTEMPTED?\nPro.lbltlenlsts Clam They Is\"a A alerIty\nof the eilslatsdrs Eleet, end Wil\nPASS STATE P1rIIIBITl\nC. I. Trldkett las le Ira rnl St Slat them\nherpose of rglngl hImr latws..\nI n Every sate.\nPress dispatches announce that -th\nAnti-Saloon League of Louisiana will\nurge sumptuary laws forLouisiana ate\nthe next meeting of the Legislature,\nand the claim is made by prominent\nofficials of the League that the esia9 e\nof prohibition has .a majority of the\nlegislators friendly to the cause.\nC. W. Trickett, of Kansas, who is\nsaid to be a forceful speaker, ha\nbeen brought South to urge this phue\nof the question, they announce, and\nhe will speak in every town; of ira\nportance in the State; both don the\nquestion on temporary local oion\nwith the eventuality of a vL\nact making entire Louisiana dr:\nHe spoke in Shreveport, Crowley\nand other cities during the past week,\nand it is certain that he will come to\nOpelousas to aid the local option a.d\nvocates in their fight in this parisb.\n\"There are fifty-nine parishes in\nthis State,\" said Dr. S, A. Smith,\nPresident of the Louislana Ari-St\nloon League and editor of the Confiict\nin New Orleans the other day, \"and\nthirty-three of them are dry, an the\nsehtiment for prohibition is rmpidly\nspreading. It is certain that we iare\na full majority in both Senatand\nHouse of the General Assembly.' \\Dr.\nSmith has so far confined his opera\ntions in New Orleans, but is conzie\nthe leader in the prohibition fightn\nthis State.\nIt is said that the bill to be intro y\nduced in the next Legislature by Judge\nPorter and Daniel Scarborough, of\nNatchitoches, the latter a member of\nthe lower house, and that Se.at.r\nBarrett, brother-in-law of Gov. Bls\nchard and a memiber of the Senate,\nwill lead the fight for the prohibi\ntionists. Senator Oglesby, Wiun;\nSenator Smart. DeSoto; Senator Elder,\nUnion; Senator Odom, Morehouse;\nSenator Glynn, Pointe Coupee, and\nSenator Bogg, Bossier, are said to a~es\nfavor the move.\nIn the House of Representatives\nHunsicker, Caddo; Payne, Winn; Rich\nardson, Bienville; Bannon and J. S.\nRichardson, are placed on the prohi\nbition side.\nKilling In Bellevue.\nTuesday night Sol Block, a negro,\nwas killed with a thirty-eight Colt's\npistol by Rufus Rudolph, in the house\nof Fannie Wilson, about three and a\nhalf miles' from town--all negroes.\nIt is not as yet knowt what was the\ncause of the shooting, but Rufus Ru\ndolph, who is now incarcerated in thel\nParish prison, admi~ j to Deputy\nGoing that he did the kilTlig.\nAnother negro, Gus Bazile, was ar\nrested for complicity in the crime.\nIt is said he shot off his pistol at or\nnear the time and place where the\nkilling occurred, and was therefore\narrested in connection therewith.\nThis makes the third or fourth\ncrime committed in the -neighbor\nhood in the last month or so-and in\ndeed the second crime within the\nweek-and it looks as if Bellevue is\ntrying to make a name for herself in\nthe Criminal Court here. It is but\nfair to state, however, that all of\nthese crimes were among negroes.\nThe question is: What is the inciting\ncause?\nFreeze Killed Boll Weevil.\nIt is the opinion of W. L. Foster,\nof near Shreveport, that the Novem\nber freeze was more destructive to\nthe boll weevil than'the recent one,\nfor the reason of the fact that the\nweevil was caught out of hibernation.\nHe informed the Shreveport Times\nthat he thought the November freeze\nhad killed fully 75 per cent of the\npesat, and had also destroyed innumer-\nable eggs.\nWhen reminded that it was stateii~\nthat a weevil could be frozen in ai\nblck of ice, ando, when thawed out,/\nwbuid Ifre, he replied that while he'\nput no faith inthe ice test, even if\nit were true, an open air freeze was\nmore severe. He said he picked\nhandfuls of the dead weevil after the.\nNovember freeze.\nAt Basptist Churbch.\nRegular services at Baptist Chiurch\nto-morrow. Sunday School at 10 a. m.\nPreaching at 11 a. m. and 8 p. m.\nOld time congregational singing, with\nspecial music. Solo by Misa Lot.r\nEverybody invited to attend these\nservices. W.R. BROWN, Pastor.,","height":"24480","width":"17736"}}
